  abstract      = {Nearly two-thirds of organizations report that they have zero trust implementations, yet higher education faces unique challenges due to expanding online enrollment. Zero trust represents a fundamental shift from traditional castle-and-moat security models: rather than trusting users once inside the network perimeter, this approach requires continuous authentication and validation of all users and assets. Universities experience rapid user turnover (25\% annually) and tight budgets, making implementation complex. Zero trust is not a product or a service but rather an ongoing organizational strategy requiring leadership buy-in and phased implementation.},
