  abstract      = {The UNESCO Recommendation on Open Science, adopted 23 November 2021, defines open science as an inclusive construct that combines various movements and practices aiming to make multilingual scientific knowledge openly available, accessible and reusable for everyone. It encompasses five pillars: open scientific knowledge (free access to publications, research data, software, and educational resources), open science infrastructures (shared facilities and digital platforms), science communication (dissemination to broader audiences), open engagement (involving societal actors beyond traditional scientific communities), and open dialogue (respecting diverse knowledge systems, including indigenous knowledge). Member States are encouraged to develop enabling policy environments, invest in digital infrastructures and human capacity, foster cultural shifts in research evaluation, promote international cooperation, and ensure equitable access regardless of geography or wealth.},
