  abstract      = {The United Nations Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities (CRPD), adopted 13 December 2006 and entered into force 3 May 2008, is a human rights instrument with an explicit social development dimension. It marks the movement from viewing persons with disabilities as objects of charity, medical treatment and social protection towards viewing them as subjects with rights. The Convention adopts a broad categorisation of persons with disabilities and reaffirms that all persons with all types of disabilities must enjoy all human rights and fundamental freedoms. It clarifies how existing rights apply specifically to people with disabilities, identifies areas requiring adaptation, and highlights protections that must be strengthened. Negotiated in record time (2002--2006), it achieved 82 signatories on its opening day and currently has 193 ratifications.},
