  abstract      = {This is Craig Brod's pioneering 1984 book "Technostress: The Human Cost of the Computer Revolution," which introduced the concept of technostress as a modern disease of adaptation caused by an inability to cope with new computer technologies in a healthy manner. Brod identified two manifestations of technostress: overidentification with computers and computer anxiety, and examined how computerization affects individuals' time orientation, communication patterns, and interpersonal relationships. The book is foundational to understanding the psychological impact of IT systems on university staff and students, particularly in the context of accelerating digital transformation of academic infrastructure.},
