  abstract     = {Brazil's Access to Information Law (Lei de Acesso à Informação), Federal Law No. 12.527 of 18 November 2011, regulating the constitutional right of access to public information. It binds all federal, state and municipal public bodies and entities, including federal universities, to the principle of publicity as the rule and secrecy as the exception, mandating active (proactive) and passive (on-request) transparency, use of information technology for disclosure, and defined response deadlines for information requests. The Comptroller General of the Union (Controladoria-Geral da União, CGU) is the principal monitoring authority at federal level. Cited as the Brazilian transparency / access-to-information functional-obligation instrument, with Law 9.784/1999 applying subsidiarily to its procedures.},
  note         = {Transparency functional obligation; CGU is the federal oversight authority. Procedural gaps are filled subsidiarily by the federal administrative-procedure law (Lei 9.784/1999).},
  fetch_status = {VERIFIED},
